      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Albany Rebel's Fall From Power'' (news article, June 8):</p>
        <p>Historically, both the Democratic speaker of the State Assembly and the Republican leader of the State Senate have used their respective powers to maintain control. Distribution of perks like committee chairmanships, hiring of staff members, fund-raising, taxpayer-financed constituent mailings and financing of local pork-barrel projects is enough to keep most party faithful in line. When Assemblyman Michael J. Bragman bravely took the high road to real reform, most of his colleagues retreated.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Albany Rebel's Fall From Power'' (news article, June 8):</p>
        <p>Historically, both the Democratic speaker of the State Assembly and the Republican leader of the State Senate have used their respective powers to maintain control. Distribution of perks like committee chairmanships, hiring of staff members, fund-raising, taxpayer-financed constituent mailings and financing of local pork-barrel projects is enough to keep most party faithful in line. When Assemblyman Michael J. Bragman bravely took the high road to real reform, most of his colleagues retreated.</p>
        <p>Completion of the 2000 census will result in new state legislative district boundaries. State Assembly Democrats traditionally gerrymander their district boundaries to maintain a majority. Republicans in charge of the State Senate do the same. Unless an independent group controls the reapportionment process, Albany will remain in the status quo for another 10 years.</p>
        <p>LARRY PENNER  Great Neck, N.Y., June 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
